Scott: Um, then, yeah, it's probably the best Metroid game, but if you say, well, look at what the games were when Super Metroid came out, it's like Super Metroid was punching way above its time, right?

562
00:46:18,048 --> 00:46:20,778
Rym: Super Metroid was like a decade ahead of its time.

563
00:46:21,200 --> 00:46:21,481
Scott: Right.

564
00:46:21,501 --> 00:46:23,850
Scott: You know, Metroid Dread, is it ahead of its time?

565
00:46:23,970 --> 00:46:24,573
Scott: Not really.

566
00:46:24,693 --> 00:46:26,280
Scott: It's just sort of, it's at its time.

567
00:46:26,300 --> 00:46:28,870
Rym: It's exactly what I wanted to play right now.

568
00:46:29,030 --> 00:46:29,211
Scott: Right.

569
00:46:29,772 --> 00:46:33,003
Scott: It's, it's just, it's the Metroid experience, right?

570
00:46:33,324 --> 00:46:36,092
Scott: Polished extremely heavily, right?

571
00:46:36,714 --> 00:46:38,640
Scott: Uh, and that's it, right?

572
00:46:38,660 --> 00:46:46,204
Rym: Like very similar to, uh, not to harp on this, uh, Castlevania games, like the other half of the Metroidvania type of world.

573
00:46:46,706 --> 00:46:49,517
Rym: We had Symphony of the Night, which was phenomenal.

574
00:46:49,758 --> 00:46:53,653
Rym: There's a bunch of other 2D Metroid, or Metroids, Castlevanias that came after that.

575
00:46:54,014 --> 00:46:54,918
Rym: They're really good.

576
00:46:55,018 --> 00:47:03,088
Rym: Some of them might even be equal to, or in some ways, some narrow ways, I'm being very specific here, better than Symphony of the Night.

577
00:47:03,369 --> 00:47:14,987
Rym: However, if you look at what existed in that genre or that space before Symphony of the Night, Symphony of the Night was like an alien from space coming down and handing onto us a new artifact.

578
00:47:15,669 --> 00:47:16,693
Scott: Except for Super Metroid.

579
00:47:17,074 --> 00:47:27,225
Rym: Yeah, but, but it was, it was a super, there's a reason why the power of Super Metroid and Castlevania became a genre that to this day we call Metroidvania.

580
00:47:27,245 --> 00:47:27,606
Rym: Right.

581
00:47:28,248 --> 00:47:28,590
Scott: Yeah.

582
00:47:28,650 --> 00:47:43,042
Scott: So, I mean, you know, if you like a Metroid game, Metroid Dread is going to give you, you know, terms of controls in terms of graphics, in terms of, you know, design, music, you know, everything is pretty much, you know, as good as it's going to be.

583
00:47:43,364 --> 00:47:43,625
Scott: Right.

584
00:47:43,826 --> 00:47:47,839
Scott: You know, there is, you will find no flaw on this heavily polished stone.

585
00:47:48,642 --> 00:47:53,863
Scott: At least no like, you know, flaw that you can say is sort of like a universal objective flaw.

586
00:47:53,904 --> 00:47:55,692
Scott: Like, ah, this, you know, there's something wrong with it.

587
00:47:55,732 --> 00:47:55,893
Scott: Right.

588
00:47:56,334 --> 00:48:02,114
Scott: However, for at least me personally, you know, this is what I mentioned last time I talked about it.

589
00:48:02,155 --> 00:48:07,574
Scott: There are a few things that for me make it only second best to Super Metroid probably.

590
00:48:07,614 --> 00:48:07,815
Scott: Right.

591
00:48:07,855 --> 00:48:11,991
Scott: So the first is that, you know, there's a plot and it's not a bad plot.

592
00:48:12,413 --> 00:48:15,626
Scott: Um, it's a better plot than some of the like Metroid Fusion, for example.

593
00:48:15,988 --> 00:48:21,394
Rym: I like in the beginning how the plot is given to you in drips and drabs and typical video gamey way, like, oh, here's the computer.

594
00:48:21,454 --> 00:48:29,144
Rym: It tells you some stuff, but then there's a point where bird uncle shows up and just spends like four minutes just telling you what's happening.

595
00:48:29,626 --> 00:48:29,907
Scott: Yeah.

596
00:48:30,068 --> 00:48:41,723
Scott: It's like, but the like Rym said, given to you in basically cut scenes, talking, voice acting, these sorts of things, Super Metroid, part of the magic of Super Metroid.

597
00:48:41,924 --> 00:48:46,419
Scott: And I am going to compare this game to Super Metroid a lot, which is fair, right?

598
00:48:46,900 --> 00:48:53,268
Scott: Uh, Super Metroid, the only plot that they give you in like, and part of it was the technological limitations of the Super Nintendo.

599
00:48:53,288 --> 00:49:07,899
Scott: You couldn't really have a video cut scene with voice acting so easily, um, and not use up all the memory on the cartridge, but the only really plot it gives you in text form is just, you know, uh, that one voice acting at the beginning, right?

600
00:49:07,919 --> 00:49:09,687
Scott: Where it's like the last Metroid is in captivity.

601
00:49:09,727 --> 00:49:10,751
Scott: The galaxy is at peace.

602
00:49:11,133 --> 00:49:18,315
Scott: And then some text, a little bit of text and every, all the rest of the story is told to you in game.

603
00:49:18,436 --> 00:49:19,880
Scott: It's like, they don't cut away.

604
00:49:19,960 --> 00:49:23,150
Scott: It's like, you know, spoilers are Super Metroid, right?

605
00:49:23,230 --> 00:49:27,850
Scott: When the baby Metroid that was at the end of Metroid two comes back and it's enormous, right?

606
00:49:27,930 --> 00:49:29,298
Scott: It's like, you just see it there.

607
00:49:29,418 --> 00:49:31,570
Scott: You can, you're still Sam is you're still looking at the game.

608
00:49:31,610 --> 00:49:32,494
Scott: You're still walking around.

609
00:49:32,515 --> 00:49:34,143
Scott: You can try to shoot it and everything, right?

610
00:49:34,505 --> 00:49:35,971
Scott: It's like, it's right there.

611
00:49:36,312 --> 00:49:43,072
Scott: You know, it's in the plot of Super Metroid is integrated into the gameplay the same way that half-life.

612
00:49:43,353 --> 00:49:44,477
Scott: one and two do it.

613
00:49:44,538 --> 00:49:50,737
Scott: Half-life does it a little bit less good, you know, cause they do, they trap you in a room and make guys talk to you sometimes.

614
00:49:51,279 --> 00:49:58,120
Scott: Um, but even so, in my opinion, that is the right way to have a plot in a video game.

615
00:49:58,421 --> 00:50:01,772
Scott: A cut scene just makes it less of a game and more of a movie.

616
00:50:02,355 --> 00:50:09,240
Scott: Um, Metroid Dread doesn't have, isn't like some ridiculous, you know, Metal Gear cut scene thing where this cut scene is all over the place.

617
00:50:09,842 --> 00:50:15,869
Rym: Um, you know, it's mostly not cut scenes, but like when you beat a boss, you're playing the game, fighting the boss the whole time.

618
00:50:15,889 --> 00:50:24,102
Rym: But when you finally beat the boss, most of the time it cuts to like a really mini cut scene that shows how bad ass Samus is doing the things that you can't do with the controller.

619
00:50:24,904 --> 00:50:25,145
Scott: Yeah.

620
00:50:25,767 --> 00:50:33,408
Scott: Um, but yeah, a lot of the plot is told to you with cut scenes as opposed to environmental storytelling.

621
00:50:33,789 --> 00:50:35,737
Scott: And that to me is a negative, right?

622
00:50:35,978 --> 00:50:39,614
Scott: I like the environmental storytelling better where you're just playing the game the whole time.

623
00:50:39,815 --> 00:50:40,439
Scott: The second thing is...

624
00:50:40,459 --> 00:50:43,855
Rym: Even the original Metroid, like why are there these weird bird statues everywhere?

625
00:50:44,858 --> 00:50:45,782
Scott: Right, exactly.

626
00:50:45,802 --> 00:50:46,343
Scott: Right.

627
00:50:46,524 --> 00:50:49,856
Scott: Whereas here it's like the bird statues are these beings called Chozo.

628
00:50:50,037 --> 00:50:50,720
Scott: Here's one of them.

629
00:50:50,821 --> 00:50:51,885
Scott: It's talking to you now.

630
00:50:51,905 --> 00:50:55,983
Rym: Of course the original Metroid, you couldn't even know what they were at all.

631
00:50:56,023 --> 00:50:57,208
Rym: It wasn't even really that good.

632
00:50:57,249 --> 00:50:58,976
Scott: You could, because it was in the instruction manual.

633
00:50:58,996 --> 00:50:59,398
Rym: Ah, yes.

634
00:50:59,458 --> 00:51:03,537
Rym: A bunch of text exposition that was given to you in a physical cut scene.

635
00:51:03,738 --> 00:51:07,194
Scott: But the instruction, all the instruction manual told you is like, it's Chozo.

636
00:51:07,436 --> 00:51:08,643
Scott: And you're like, what the fuck is Chozo?

637
00:51:08,704 --> 00:51:09,650
Scott: It didn't tell you anything else.

638
00:51:10,510 --> 00:51:28,666
Scott: Regardless, the second thing is that other Metroid games, even Super Metroid to a large extent, um, there's bad guys that are just, you know, the non-boss bad guys, uh, are, you know, all over the place, but they're largely not a threat to you ever.

639
00:51:28,887 --> 00:51:29,910
Rym: Unless you're not cautious.

640
00:51:30,211 --> 00:51:34,552
Rym: Like if you're just like not that good or not paying attention or getting lazy, it's easy to bump into them.

641
00:51:35,294 --> 00:51:35,615
Scott: Yeah.

642
00:51:35,696 --> 00:51:41,676
Scott: But for the most part, like the bad guys in Metroid games are just sort of decorations on the level, right?

643
00:51:41,696 --> 00:51:46,916
Scott: They give you something to do, a reason to shoot your gun when it's not a boss, right?

644
00:51:46,936 --> 00:51:49,286
Scott: Just like, Oh, there's a bad guys in this room.

645
00:51:49,386 --> 00:51:53,303
Scott: I guess I have to push the shoot button a few times to get to the other side of the room.

646
00:51:53,363 --> 00:51:54,427
Scott: I can't just run across.

647
00:51:54,588 --> 00:51:57,101
Rym: It gives you a natural sense of progression.

648
00:51:57,161 --> 00:52:05,021
Rym: And then as you just get better at the game, you can move through areas you've been through where there's enemies, you know how to handle faster or competently with less thought.

649
00:52:05,323 --> 00:52:10,669
Rym: Like you just sort of memorize a pattern or no, you can run past a certain guy or you have a better upgraded weapon at that point.

650
00:52:10,689 --> 00:52:17,756
Rym: And they go down easier, but it does give you a sense of progression that you wouldn't get if you were just exploring and fighting bosses.

651
00:52:18,479 --> 00:52:18,639
Scott: Yep.

652
00:52:19,081 --> 00:52:24,679
Scott: But for the most part, the bad guys aren't part of the challenge of a Metroid game, the normal bad guys.

653
00:52:25,522 --> 00:52:29,635
Scott: They're just, you know, decoration, environment stuff, right?

654
00:52:30,798 --> 00:52:34,126
Scott: Whereas in Metroid Dread, the regular old bad guys.

655
00:52:34,667 --> 00:52:42,968
Scott: for, you know, as you progress through the game, if you backtrack to an area where there's weaker bad guys than your current equipment, yeah, they're just going to be decoration.

656
00:52:43,028 --> 00:52:58,763
Scott: But as you're progressing through the game, the regular old bad guys are like in your way, you have to get past them and you have to actually do a little bit of like action game button timing stuff to get to defeat them, right?

657
00:52:59,124 --> 00:53:02,096
Scott: They're not necessarily difficult, though there is a hard mode.

658
00:53:02,116 --> 00:53:05,012
Scott: you can unlock after you beat the game, which probably does make them more difficult.

659
00:53:05,032 --> 00:53:10,422
Rym: But they also, when they hit you, especially in an area you haven't fully explored yet that you're currently supposed to be in, they'll mess you up.

660
00:53:10,462 --> 00:53:13,435
Rym: They do a shit ton of damage, way more than I expected.

661
00:53:13,455 --> 00:53:14,821
Scott: Even on not hard mode, right?

662
00:53:14,881 --> 00:53:16,910
Scott: If you mess up, then you pay the price.

663
00:53:17,611 --> 00:53:19,294
Scott: Yeah.

664
00:53:19,975 --> 00:53:26,928
Scott: And also, right, the bosses are very much, you know, the classic action game.

665
00:53:27,288 --> 00:53:31,401
Scott: Simon says, you see this animation, that means you have to do this.

666
00:53:31,843 --> 00:53:39,966
Scott: That means slide, that means jump, that means dash to evade that enemy's attack, that means shoot him now, right?

667
00:53:41,049 --> 00:53:44,259
Scott: And that's how you defeat enemies because that's how action games work, right?

668
00:53:45,584 --> 00:53:48,713
Scott: And then you also have some timing things, right?

669
00:53:48,733 --> 00:53:51,343
Scott: It's like when you see a flash, push X to counter attack.

670
00:53:51,966 --> 00:53:59,494
Scott: You also have a little bit of quick time event things at certain parts in little cut scenes here and there, not too much, very small amount.

671
00:53:59,595 --> 00:54:04,136
Rym: Yeah, we'll describe the enemy thing because I think there's some interesting game mechanics stuff to talk about there.

672
00:54:04,398 --> 00:54:06,870
Rym: There's good and bad parts of that aspect of this game.

673
00:54:06,970 --> 00:54:13,194
Scott: Right, but the point I'm making is that this Metroid is much more of an action game than other Metroids.

674
00:54:13,254 --> 00:54:20,562
Scott: where the action parts are, you can just sort of gloss over them and just, it's more, the exploring is what matters.

675
00:54:20,582 --> 00:54:33,778
Rym: Because one specific thing I noticed in this Metroid compared to other Metroids I have played is that in this one, you know, the typical fashion, you get items that lets you interact with or get past obstacles you couldn't get past before, kind of like in a Zelda 3.

676
00:54:33,778 --> 00:54:36,790
Rym: Now you can go back and go to an area you couldn't go to before, like.

677
00:54:36,810 --> 00:54:38,075
Rym: that's a big part of the game loop.

678
00:54:38,637 --> 00:54:48,617
Rym: But in older Metroids, you could explore a lot more broadly and when you got a new item, the game didn't do a ton of work to point you in the right direction of where you could use it.

679
00:54:48,658 --> 00:54:53,536
Rym: It kind of assumed you'd explore and figure stuff out, backtrack on your own, etc.

680
00:54:53,958 --> 00:55:11,355
Rym: This game often, when you solve a puzzle in a certain area, it'll, you get to a certain point in these areas, it'll block paths in that area to really push you into backtracking toward where the interesting stuff is that you can interact with the things you recently acquired.

681
00:55:11,816 --> 00:55:22,279
Rym: So, it'll like, you find a teleporter pad early in the game, the first one, and as soon as you use it, a bunch of shit falls down and blocks the path back, so you're forced to go forward in the area you just got to.

682
00:55:22,681 --> 00:55:23,644
Rym: That happens a lot.

683
00:55:24,086 --> 00:55:35,189
Rym: You can often get around those blocks if you really want to backtrack and get the one thing the game's guiding you away from, but it's often tedious, so I tend to just go where the game wants me to go.

684
00:55:35,590 --> 00:55:41,310
Rym: But it did remove a small aspect of exploration that I did enjoy more in other Metroid games.

685
00:55:41,310 --> 00:55:50,007
Scott: At a certain point, the game does sort of unlock and you can go anywhere freely, but yeah, at least they did a better job of that than Metroid Fusion does.

686
00:55:50,067 --> 00:55:55,164
Scott: Metroid Fusion literally, you're locked in this zone, now go to the next zone.

687
00:55:55,184 --> 00:56:03,770
Scott: Whereas this did the same concept, but made it feel more natural and integrated, but it still was, I still prefer Super Metroid.

688
00:56:03,990 --> 00:56:05,920
Scott: It's like, you can just go anywhere that you can go.

689
00:56:05,940 --> 00:56:11,270
Scott: It's up to you to remember where, or figure out where the, you know, remember there was a green door you couldn't open.

690
00:56:11,571 --> 00:56:12,755
Scott: You just got super missile.

691
00:56:13,057 --> 00:56:14,362
Scott: Where was that green door again?

692
00:56:14,382 --> 00:56:15,165
Scott: Oh, right.

693
00:56:15,286 --> 00:56:16,330
Scott: It was over in that place.

694
00:56:16,370 --> 00:56:18,016
Scott: Let me go to that place and use my green.

695
00:56:18,056 --> 00:56:24,320
Rym: It is hard to express how fucking jazzed I was to be able to open green doors, right?

696
00:56:24,641 --> 00:56:26,789
Rym: That's that's so those green doors, the whole game.

697
00:56:26,829 --> 00:56:27,632
Rym: And I'm just like, damn it.

698
00:56:27,893 --> 00:56:28,776
Rym: How do I get in there?

699
00:56:29,197 --> 00:56:31,605
Scott: But anyway, so it's more of an action game.

700
00:56:32,147 --> 00:56:38,707
Scott: And the, the action game that it is, is an extremely polished, high quality action game.

701
00:56:38,727 --> 00:56:39,971
Scott: Like there aren't much better.

702
00:56:39,991 --> 00:56:43,765
Scott: I just personally, I'm not playing Metroid for the action.

703
00:56:43,805 --> 00:56:48,827
Scott: So I'm a, it's like, yeah, they put in like one of the best possible action games.

704
00:56:48,867 --> 00:56:49,510
Scott: That's amazing.

705
00:56:49,910 --> 00:56:53,310
Scott: But I would rather have that personally, I'd rather have there be no action game.

706
00:56:53,571 --> 00:56:56,264
Scott: It's like, I want the enemies that don't really challenge me.

707
00:56:56,385 --> 00:56:58,594
Scott: I want to just, I want, I'm there for the explorer.

708
00:56:58,754 --> 00:57:00,159
Rym: You want just like an Odyssey?

709
00:57:00,962 --> 00:57:01,183
Scott: Yeah.

710
00:57:01,243 --> 00:57:08,329
Scott: Well, I mean, I'm not there for, you know, shooting the regular old bad guys or for a really complicated boss.

711
00:57:08,389 --> 00:57:10,377
Scott: I'm just, I just want to fill the boss full of missiles.

712
00:57:10,457 --> 00:57:10,658
Scott: Right.

713
00:57:10,698 --> 00:57:13,530
Scott: It's like, you know, there's a bad guy.

714
00:57:13,731 --> 00:57:13,852
Scott: Yeah.

715
00:57:13,872 --> 00:57:14,134
Scott: Okay.

716
00:57:14,154 --> 00:57:15,080
Scott: I'll shoot the bad guy.

717
00:57:15,141 --> 00:57:18,158
Scott: But it's like, I don't want to have to have like the dual with this regular old bad guy.

718
00:57:18,178 --> 00:57:27,372
Rym: And you know, it's like, but I also don't, I don't want to go back to original Metroid one on the NES of you better have 90 missiles and you don't miss with any of them.

719
00:57:27,392 --> 00:57:27,472
Rym: Yeah.

720
00:57:28,997 --> 00:57:31,765
Rym: That's also the wrong Ridley in that game sucks.

721
00:57:32,347 --> 00:57:37,903
Scott: There's a reason I'm comparing to super Metroid, not regular one is you don't need to read this.

722
00:57:37,984 --> 00:57:40,592
Rym: Not like most Metro games are playing.

723
00:57:40,993 --> 00:57:44,327
Rym: You don't really need to go back and beat the original Metroid.

724
00:57:44,347 --> 00:57:50,655
Scott: You, what you, what you should do is you should play the original Metroid a little bit so you can understand what it was like.

725
00:57:51,137 --> 00:57:53,405
Rym: That'll tell you everything you needed to know about that game.

726
00:57:54,047 --> 00:57:55,512
Scott: Then play Metroid zero mission.

